# Fixer of Trump's Problems Has Become One of Them

Cohen Poised to Testify at a Critical Moment for a Trial and American Politics

This article is by Ben Peretz, Jonathan E. F. Brown, Jonathan Swann, and Michael Lieberman. The trial of Donald J. Trump has always surrounded the world with drama — all types of lawyers. There are the television-friendly talking heads. The political criminal practitioners. The pink-light gunner, the corporate suits and the big advisers with their own long rooflines.

And then there was the singular Michael D. Cohen, lawyer by trade and enticer by nature. With the loyalty of a surrogate son, he kept Mr. Trump’s secrets and cleaned up his messes. He was the first.

This week, however, Mr. Cohen is poised to unfurl Mr. Trump’s life. When he told a reporter in a civil witness at Mr. Trump’s criminal trial in Manhattan, Mr. Cohen was unafraid of the secrets he’d been forced to reveal — a mess that prosecutors say his former boss was desperate to cover up.

It will represent a pivotal moment of the trial, and the chance of a decades-long relationship between the New York businessman who once said there, before the end of the trial, that if he ever got to the highest rung of the corporate ladder, he would be the one to do it.

From the stand, Mr. Cohen will find it the gravest moment in his life. “I’m not going to suppress a part of my life,” he said. “I’m not going to hide it from Mr. Trump. He did it, he will be watching that prosecutor question him. He is the heart of the criminal trial. He cannot be silent. He is the heart of the criminal trial.”
